umap_coords = ad.obsm['X_umap']

# Step 3: Order cells by trajectory (or milestone_id)
# Assuming milestone_ids represent the trajectory positions
milestone_ids = ad.uns['cell_info']['milestone_id'].astype(str)  # Make sure the milestone IDs are strings or sorted

# Sort cells by milestone progression (if they are ordered numerically or categorically)
sorted_idx = np.argsort(milestone_ids)
ordered_umap_coords = umap_coords[sorted_idx]

# Step 4: Identify start and terminal cells
start_milestone = np.min(milestone_ids)  # The first milestone
end_milestone = np.max(milestone_ids)    # The last milestone

# Find the indices of the start and terminal cells
start_cells = np.where(milestone_ids == start_milestone)[0]
end_cells = np.where(milestone_ids == end_milestone)[0]

# Step 5: Plot trajectory path
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

# Plot the trajectory as a line connecting cells along the trajectory
plt.plot(ordered_umap_coords[:, 0], ordered_umap_coords[:, 1], 
         color='grey', alpha=0.6, linewidth=1)

# Now plot the cells with milestone color
milestone_colors = {milestone: plt.cm.jet(i / len(np.unique(milestone_ids))) 
                    for i, milestone in enumerate(np.unique(milestone_ids))}

# Plot each milestone with its corresponding color
for milestone in np.unique(milestone_ids):
    cells = milestone_ids == milestone
    plt.scatter(ordered_umap_coords[cells, 0], ordered_umap_coords[cells, 1], 
                label=f'Milestone {milestone}', 
                color=milestone_colors[milestone], alpha=0.7, s=20)

# Highlight start and terminal cells with distinct markers
plt.scatter(ordered_umap_coords[start_cells, 0], ordered_umap_coords[start_cells, 1], 
            color='green', label='Start', s=50, edgecolor='black', marker='o')
plt.scatter(ordered_umap_coords[end_cells, 0], ordered_umap_coords[end_cells, 1], 
            color='red', label='Terminal', s=50, edgecolor='black', marker='X')

# Add title, labels, and legend
plt.title("Trajectory on UMAP projection")
plt.xlabel("UMAP 1")
plt.ylabel("UMAP 2")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
